stic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Neville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Neuville in Calvados or Néville in Seine-Maritime, both so called from Old French <i>neu(f)</i> ‘new’ (from Latin <i>novus</i>) + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. One family line, originally from Neuville (Calvados), became powerful during the Wars of the Roses through Richard <i>Neville</i> (1428–71), 16th Earl of Warwick, nicknamed \"The Kingmaker\".","Irish (Munster): assimilation of the Gaelic name <b>Ó Niadh</b> (see   Nee  ) and sometimes of <b>Ó Cnaimhín</b> (see   Nevin  ).","History: George Neville came to VA in or <i>c.</i> 1700 and settled on the headwaters of the Occoquan River, acquiring a large estate. His descendants, bearing the surnames Neville and Craig, were of considerable importance in Pittsburgh, PA, and Cincinnati, OH."],"variants":[{"name":"Nevells","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevils","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Novel","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  .","Catalan: variant of   Novell  ."]},{"name":"Newell","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  .","English: variant of   Noel  .","English: variant of   Newhall  ."]},{"name":"Nevills","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Nevil","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Newill","meanings":["English and Irish (or Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevill","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevels","meanings":["English and Scottish (Wigtownshire): of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Dutch and North German: unexplained."]},{"name":"Nee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, John Patrick.","Irish (Galway): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Niadh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Nia</i>’ or <b>Mac Niadh</b> ‘son of <i>Nia</i>’. Compare   McNee  .   Needham   2 and   Neville   have also been adopted as Anglicized forms of this name.","North German: possibly a relationship name from Middle Low German <i>neve</i> ‘nephew, grand-child’."]}]},{"name":"Isabella","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."],"variants":[{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Isabella de Neville was born about 1010. She married Richard de Neville about 1045, in Néville-sur-Mer, Manche, Lower Normandy, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1010–":"umbes 1010–Surnud","1025–1066":"1025–1066","1042–1118":"1042–1118","1010–Female":"1010–Surnud","1118":"1118","Abt 1042":"umbes 1042","1025":"1025","1066":"1066","1010":"1010","1042":"1042","about 1010":"umbes 1010","about 1045":"umbes 1045","Néville-sur-Mer, Manche, Lower Normandy, France":"Néville-sur-Mer, Manche, Basse-Normandie